abstract: Britain's mid-tier banks have asked the Bank of England to ease rules introduced after the financial crisis that they say hamper their efforts to compete with bigger rivals that have a tight grip on the market.
snippet: Britain's mid-tier banks have asked the Bank of England to ease rules introduced after the financial crisis that they say hamper their efforts to compete with bigger rivals that have a tight grip on the market.
lead_paragraph: LONDON — Britain's mid-tier banks have asked the Bank of England to ease rules introduced after the financial crisis that they say hamper their efforts to compete with bigger rivals that have a tight grip on the market.
headline_main: Small British Banks Want Softer Rules to Help Them Compete
headline_print_headline: Small British Banks Want Softer Rules to Help Them Compete

abstract: The violence ended at a kosher market where three bystanders were slain. The mayor said the attackers had “targeted the location.”
snippet: The violence ended at a kosher market where three bystanders were slain. The mayor said the attackers had “targeted the location.”
lead_paragraph: The shooting began outside a cemetery in Jersey City, N.J., on Tuesday when a 40-year-old detective tried to intercept two people who were suspects in a homicide. They opened fire and fled, speeding off in a rented truck that had been reported stolen and leaving the detective dead on the ground.

abstract: Chevron Corp. said Tuesday it will book a charge of at least $10 billion because lower long-term prices for oil and natural gas will reduce the value of its assets.
snippet: Chevron Corp. said Tuesday it will book a charge of at least $10 billion because lower long-term prices for oil and natural gas will reduce the value of its assets.
lead_paragraph: SAN RAMON, Calif. — Chevron Corp. said Tuesday it will book a charge of at least $10 billion because lower long-term prices for oil and natural gas will reduce the value of its assets.
headline_main: Chevron Will Write Down Assets By at Least $10 Billion
headline_print_headline: Chevron Will Write Down Assets By at Least $10 Billion

abstract: In the waning weeks before South Carolina's presidential primary, Democrat Tom Steyer is renewing his focus on the black voters who play a pivotal role in the first-in-the-South state, rolling out a proposal to improve historically black colleges and institutions.
snippet: In the waning weeks before South Carolina's presidential primary, Democrat Tom Steyer is renewing his focus on the black voters who play a pivotal role in the first-in-the-South state, rolling out a proposal to improve historically black colleges ...
lead_paragraph: COLUMBIA, S.C. — In the waning weeks before South Carolina's presidential primary, Democrat Tom Steyer is renewing his focus on the black voters who play a pivotal role in the first-in-the-South state, rolling out a proposal to improve historically black colleges and institutions.
headline_main: In South Carolina, Steyer Investing in Black Voters
headline_print_headline: In South Carolina, Steyer Investing in Black Voters

abstract: He cleared a final polling hurdle to join six other candidates, ensuring there won’t be an all-white debate.
snippet: He cleared a final polling hurdle to join six other candidates, ensuring there won’t be an all-white debate.
lead_paragraph: The entrepreneur Andrew Yang has qualified for next week’s Democratic debate, bringing the lineup to seven and ensuring that the candidates onstage will not all be white, though the lineup still does not include any black or Latino candidates.

abstract: The winner of this year's Nobel Peace Prize says his horrifying experiences as a young Ethiopian soldier fueled his determination to seek an end to the long conflict with a neighboring country.

lead_paragraph: Gail Collins: Bret, how do you feel about billionaires? Not personally — I’m sure some of your best friends are billionaires — but as presidential candidates. Ever since Michael Bloomberg started running, there’s been a lot of complaining about rich guys trying to buy the race. Does that worry you, or do you find people like Bloomberg and Tom Steyer to be, um, valuable additions?
